description:
There are two Duskywing butterflies in this area that are very similar... at least to my eye!
I have recently found a specimen of each and got a clear shot of the wing design.  I now believe this one is a Mournful Duskywing due to the pattern of white spots on the forewing and absence of white markings at the posterior edge of the hindwing.
This lizard, which I believe to be a male, was spotted in the near vicinity of another, less colorful, specimen that I assumed to be a female.

On a hike into the Verdugo Hills, I saw a number of Side-Blotched Lizards in close proximity. I believe this one is a female. The sub-photo shows a large dark blue blotch behind the front leg from which the species derives its name.
Saw this tiny guy (only12 to 14 inches in length) crossing the trail on a sunny spring afternoon.

calyx 13 mm
corolla tube 8 mm, lobes 8 mm

calyx 12 mm

calyx 14 mm
corolla tube 9.5 mm, lobes 9.5 mm

calyx 12 mm
corolla tube 8 mm, lobes 6 mm.

description: With a low sun in the western sky a Pipevine Swallowtail is casting a long shadow as it's puddling in mud at what was previously a flooded area at Mississippi Bar, the eastern end of the "Rim trail".
Seen in a previously flooded area at Mississippi Bar, the eastern end of the "RIm trail".
Another separate observation later in the afternoon of a Painted Lady feeding on Blue Dicks.

First observation this year of the Pipevine Swallowtail at Mississippi Bar,near Lake Natoma.This one is actively feeding on Blue Dicks (Dichelostemma capitatum) that is abundantly growing in this area.

This is my first observation of a Spring first brood Acmon Blue this year at Mississippi Bar.The Host plant here for the Acmon Blue is Spanish Lotus (Acmispon americanus).  Interestingly 
the low angle of the sun in the west is back lighting
the wings for an interesting ventral view.

These are the first sightings of the migration of Painted Lady that has made it's way north from the desert southwest into Southern California to now Mississippi Bar near Lake Natoma. There are an abundance of Blue Dicks (Dichelostemma capitatum) for these new arrivals to feed on before they continue their journey north.
Popcorn Flowers at Mississippi Bar is a food source for a variety of butterflies that frequent this area.
This area of Mississippi Bar is where some flooding has occurred.After the water receded Red Maids can now be seen growing well throughout this area.

This is an area of local flooding at Mississippi Bar. As of this date we are at 120% of normal rainfall with 20.25 inches in the Sacramento area. These Mallards are enjoying this extra water that has accumulated.
